You're a system administrator responsible for managing a server hosting a website. Your tasks include managing files, directories, permissions, and monitoring system resources.

Commands and Short Notes:
1. ls
Usage: ls [options] [file/directory]
Short Note: Lists files and directories in the current directory.
Example: ls -l
2. cd
Usage: cd [directory]
Short Note: Changes the current directory.
Example: cd /var/www/html
3. mkdir
Usage: mkdir [directory]
Short Note: Creates a new directory.
Example: mkdir images
4. touch
Usage: touch [file]
Short Note: Creates an empty file or updates the timestamp of an existing file.
Example: touch index.html
5. cp
Usage: cp [source] [destination]
Short Note: Copies files or directories.
Example: cp index.html index_backup.html
6. mv
Usage: mv [source] [destination]
Short Note: Moves or renames files or directories.
Example: mv index.html public_html/index.html
7. rm
Usage: rm [file]
Short Note: Removes files or directories.
Example: rm index_backup.html
8. chmod
Usage: chmod [mode] [file/directory]
Short Note: Changes the permissions of files or directories.
Example: chmod 755 script.sh
9. chown
Usage: chown [user:group] [file/directory]
Short Note: Changes the owner and group of files or directories.
Example: chown user:group index.html
10. grep
Usage: grep [pattern] [file]
Short Note: Searches for a pattern in files.
Example: grep "error" logfile.txt
11. ps
Usage: ps [options]
Short Note: Displays information about processes running on the system.
Example: ps aux
12. top
Usage: top
Short Note: Displays dynamic real-time information about system resources and processes.
Example: top
13. df
Usage: df [options]
Short Note: Displays information about disk space usage.
Example: df -h
14. du
Usage: du [options] [directory]
Short Note: Displays disk usage of files and directories.
Example: du -sh /var/www
